Using existing material to simplify your proof is only half the story. Sometimes it is the stuff you are adding that is improving the existing material (for example `(c.comap e).Quotient ≃* c.Quotient`). Also people might want to use results from both sides and it is useful to have a common backbone that is being built upon.

This is a general result that If `e : M →* N` is surjective then `(c.comap e).Quotient ≃* c.Quotient` with `c : Con N`.
implemented in the latest PR!

Can you add 
```
lemma eqvGen_stepsto {β : Type*} [Monoid β] (r : β → β → Prop) :
    EqvGen (PresentedMonoid.StepsTo r) = ConGen.Rel r := by
``` 
`PresentedMonoid.StepsTo` should have a different name (maybe `MulGen`?) and be moved to `GroupTheory/Congruence`
now it's implemented with Con

I still think `abbrev PresentedMonoid := (conGen rel).Quotient` is a better definition. It gives you the monoid structure and the surjection `FreeMonoid α -> PresentedMonoid rel` and the universal property for free.
done!

Sorry for the late response, but that is just [FreeMonoid.lift](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/FreeMonoid/Basic.html#FreeMonoid.lift). The reason, I am suspicious of `foldr` is that I don't think we should just duplicate the `List` API in `FreeMonoid`.
oh, I see! that makes sense, I'll remove it

I would call this PresentedMonoid.lift instead.

Happy to change it! Only reason I had it this way was to follow the PresentedGroup file, which has PresentedGroup.toGroup. Do you think it's better to match that convention, or make it the more common/clear term "lift"?

This is easier proved via [MonoidHom.eq_of_eqOn_denseM](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Group/Submonoid/Basic.html#MonoidHom.eq_of_eqOn_denseM)
oh that's nice, thank you!

done :)
Is "steps-to" closure a standard terminology? I've never heard of it.

Oy, it is not! I went back to some textbooks, and it looks like the proper term is "one-step reduction"

I've updated the definitions (thanks to your comment, I realized I had other errors too!), though it feels clunky. I'm not sure how to best describe `rels`. It's not a set - can I just call it a relation? Or is it a function? Any advice would be much appreciated!

(I may also have better ideas in the morning)

```suggestion
* `PresentedMonoid.of`: The canonical map from `α` to a presented monoid with generators `α`.
```

```suggestion
* `PresentedMonoid.lift f`: the canonical monoid homomorphism `PresentedMonoid rels → M`, given a function
```

additive monoid. That is, the additive submonoid closure of the set of generators equals `⊤`"]
